<statement>
<image width="33%" pi:generated="problems/images/mom-1057071-1.png"/><p>
Suppose a = 4 and c = 11. Calculate:</p>
<p>
b = <fillin characters="20"/></p>
<p>
A = <fillin characters="20"/> degrees</p>
<p>
B = <fillin characters="20"/> degrees</p>
<p>
Round all answers to one decimal place. Give angles in <em>degrees</em>.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>10.2</li><li>21.3</li><li>68.7</li></ul></p><p>First calculate the length of the other leg.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{11}^{{2}}={4}^{{2}}+{b}^{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{121}={16}+{b}^{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{121}-{16}={b}^{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{105}={b}^{{2}}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle\sqrt{{{105}}}={b}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{10.24695076596}\approx{b}</m>.</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{10.2}\approx{b}</m>.</p>
<p>For angle A</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{\arcsin{{\left(\frac{{4}}{{11}}\right)}}}\approx{21.323686263476}\approx{21.3}</m></p>
<p>For angle B</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{\arccos{{\left(\frac{{4}}{{11}}\right)}}}\approx{68.676313736524}\approx{68.7}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>